1. Stacking Buffs (Building Up vs. Consuming Down)

Right now, your consumable_charges property behaves like a countdown timer (ammunition). But many MMO effects work in reverse—they build up stacks, and the strength of the buff scales with the stack count.

    The SWTOR Example: Induction or Voltaic Currents on a Deception Assassin. Executing certain moves builds stacks (up to 2 or 3), and each stack reduces the Force cost or increases the damage of your next high-impact ability.

    The Structural Gap: You need an effect type where value is multiplied by the current stack_count, and instead of hitting 0 and popping, it caps out at a max stack limit.

2. On-Hit / On-Crit Procs (The Event Loop Bridge)

Currently, your actions have a chance modifier evaluated when cast. True MMO procs are triggered by the outcome of the hit inside calculate_hit.

    The SWTOR Example: "Your periodic damage ticks have a 30% chance to reset the cooldown of Crushing Darkness," or "Critical hits have a 100% chance to grant a stack of X."

    The Structural Gap: calculate_hit returns (damage, is_crit). Right now, that information is just printed. To handle procs, that result needs to feed back into an event dispatcher so the engine can say: "Hey, this hit was a Crit! Check if the player has any buffs that care about Crits."

3. Internal Cooldown (ICD) Effects

This is a subset of procs, highly common for endgame gear like Relics (e.g., Focused Retribution or Serendipitous Assault).

    The SWTOR Example: Your attacks have a 30% chance to grant +X Mastery for 6 seconds. This effect cannot occur more than once every 20 seconds.

    The Structural Gap: If you implement procs, you will need a way to place an individual effect on its own internal cooldown clock inside caster.cooldowns so it can't trigger back-to-back.

4. Resource Refunds & Cost Modifiers

Right now, energy_cost is a static number hardcoded directly onto the Ability instance configuration.

    The SWTOR Example: Passive skills that reduce the cost of your main abilities by 25%, or mechanics where a critical hit refunds 5 Force back to your pool.

    The Structural Gap: Before spending resources in Ability.cast(), your engine needs to pass the capability through a modifier check (similar to how you pass damage through calculate_hit) to see if any active player buffs reduce or completely waive the resource cost.

5. Execute Phase / Health Threshold Scaling

You have an explicit "sub_30" bucket mapped out inside your global EFFECTS dictionary, but the math loop isn't checking the target's actual health status yet to validate it.

    The SWTOR Example: Passives that increase your critical strike chance by 15% only if the target is below 30% health.

    The Structural Gap: Your caster.effects loop inside calculate_hit needs access to target.hp and target.max_hp to evaluate if threshold-dependent buckets like sub_30 should be factored into the active multiplier calculations.

Of these options, Stacking Buffs or Health Thresholds would be the easiest next additions since they plug right into your current design, whereas On-Hit Procs require shifting how your modules talk to each other.